1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,265
Let's now take a look at how we can use existing LLMs with hugging face.

2

00:00:05,265  -->  00:00:08,295
When it comes to using hugging face models,

3

00:00:08,295  -->  00:00:10,605
we have two options.

4

00:00:10,605  -->  00:00:17,210
First, we can use a high-level API accessible using the pipeline function.

5

00:00:17,210  -->  00:00:22,480
Or we can use a more flexible but more low-level API,

6

00:00:22,480  -->  00:00:28,960
which we would use if we want to have more control over how to use a particular model.

7

00:00:28,960  -->  00:00:31,840
Since this is a beginner-friendly lesson,

8

00:00:31,840  -->  00:00:35,780
we will focus just on using the high-level API.

9

00:00:35,780  -->  00:00:40,580
But keep in mind that hugging face API has much more to offer.

10

00:00:40,580  -->  00:00:46,040
Let's now look at how to use a large language model with a hugging face.

11

00:00:46,040  -->  00:00:52,290
First, we need to import the pipeline function from the transformers package.

12

00:00:52,290  -->  00:00:54,540
To use it, we need to call

13

00:00:54,540  -->  00:00:59,115
the pipeline function and provide the name of the task we wanted to do.

14

00:00:59,115  -->  00:01:03,420
Here we specify text generation to generate text,

15

00:01:03,420  -->  00:01:08,840
but there are other tasks we can use such as text summarization and others.

16

00:01:08,840  -->  00:01:10,820
The pipeline function returns

17

00:01:10,820  -->  00:01:16,180
another function that we can use to perform the selected task.

18

00:01:16,180  -->  00:01:21,020
We then need to specify a prompt for tax generation.

19

00:01:21,020  -->  00:01:24,280
Since we've selected the tax generation task,

20

00:01:24,280  -->  00:01:30,000
it will continue generating text that continues the selected phrase.

21

00:01:30,300  -->  00:01:33,440
To generate x using this prompt,

22

00:01:33,440  -->  00:01:36,660
we need to call the generator function returned by

23

00:01:36,660  -->  00:01:40,040
the pipeline call and provide a few parameters,

24

00:01:40,040  -->  00:01:44,420
such as a prompt, the maximum length of the output that it will generate,

25

00:01:44,420  -->  00:01:48,420
and number of sequences we wanted to generate.

26

00:01:48,700  -->  00:01:51,500
This will take the provided prompt,

27

00:01:51,500  -->  00:01:53,400
pass it to the LLM,

28

00:01:53,400  -->  00:01:56,500
and it will return a response.

29

00:01:57,900  -->  00:02:01,180
Under the hood, it goes through the steps,

30

00:02:01,180  -->  00:02:03,765
you should already be pretty familiar with.

31

00:02:03,765  -->  00:02:07,140
When hugging face receives an input text,

32

00:02:07,140  -->  00:02:12,605
it splits it into tokens using a tokenizer for the selected model.

33

00:02:12,605  -->  00:02:20,170
Converts these tokens into IDs and then passes these token IDs to the model.

34

00:02:20,170  -->  00:02:27,005
Then the model returns a set of logits that are then used to generate an output.

35

00:02:27,005  -->  00:02:31,910
Hugging phase can do a myriad of different NLP-related tasks.

36

00:02:31,910  -->  00:02:36,650
It supports tasks like text generation that we've just covered.

37

00:02:36,650  -->  00:02:40,750
Questions answering, text summarization.

38

00:02:40,750  -->  00:02:44,570
It allows to translate between different languages,

39

00:02:44,570  -->  00:02:50,550
and it supports classification of text into one of selected categories.

40

00:02:51,170  -->  00:02:56,130
We can use hugging face not only for NLP-related tasks.

41

00:02:56,130  -->  00:03:01,015
It also supports audio-related tasks like audio classification,

42

00:03:01,015  -->  00:03:04,075
and converting text to audio.

43

00:03:04,075  -->  00:03:08,630
It also allows us to work with images and videos.

44

00:03:08,630  -->  00:03:13,430
For example, we can use it to generate an image description,

45

00:03:13,430  -->  00:03:20,150
classify videos, perform image segmentation, and much more.

46

00:03:20,150  -->  00:03:26,570
Let's take a look at how to use hugging face for tasks other than generating text.

47

00:03:26,570  -->  00:03:31,425
Here is an example of how to perform image classification with hugging face.

48

00:03:31,425  -->  00:03:33,910
Again, we need to use the pipeline function,

49

00:03:33,910  -->  00:03:38,910
but here we specify a different task called image classification.

50

00:03:38,910  -->  00:03:43,790
Then we pass an image file or an image URL to classify.

51

00:03:43,790  -->  00:03:47,410
The output of this score is a list where every element

52

00:03:47,410  -->  00:03:51,890
contains a label and the probability associated with it.

53

00:03:51,890  -->  00:03:59,090
In this case, it thinks that the image we've passed to it is likely an image of a cat.
